title: For Sale/Trade:  Gen 1 Glock 17
postcontent: I have a very nice First Generation Glock 17 that I am interested in trading and/or selling. The Glock is in very nice condition and shows very little wear and has all the original black internals (no six part upgrade).  Glock was only said to make approximately 115,000 of these guns worldwide before the introduction of the gen 2 models.  Given that it is estimated Glock has produced 3-4 million guns, this represents a very small percentage.  The 17 comes with the two original 17 round magazines - these alone sometimes sell for $75 -100. These were produced before Glock went to a full metal lining and are sometimes called non-drop free mags.  Unfortunately I don't have the original 'tupperware' case.I love the 17 and many of my friends who shoot Glock s have never actually shot a Gen 1 but I also have a later 19 that I shoot most often, so perhaps it is time for my Gen 1 to go to someone who can appreciate it.  I would prefer to trade but would accept a cash offer of $550.Buyer must meet in a public place, present ID and fill out a Bill of Sale.

title: For Sale:  Walther CCP single stack delayed blow back action
postcontent: The CCP’s SOFTCOIL™ gas-delayed blowback system uses gas pressure from the ignited cartridge by directing it through a small port in the barrel in front of the chamber to slow down and delay the rearward motion of the slide. This is accomplished by means of a piston contained inside of a cylinder located under the barrel that opposes the rearward motion of the slide until the gas pressure has declined after the bullet has left the barrel. This allows the slide to end its rearward motion, opening the breech, and ejecting the empty cartridge case.

title: For Sale:  Original German Luger Holster DLU 1940 & Waffenamt 727
postcontent: For sale, original German WWII black leather Luger holster. Holster is a Vet bring back and is in very good condition, shows some wear, but overall very good condition, strap and belt loops are intact. Holster is marked on the rear DLU, 1940 and Waffenamt stamped 727, DLU is the maker’s code for the firm Ewald Luneschloss, Militar-Effekten-Fabrik, Solingen, Norderhein-Westfalen, WaA 727 was the Waffenamt assigned to Ewald Luneschloss, Solingen in 1940. The pouch for the loading tool under the flap is in excellent condition, there is also a side pouch for a spare magazine. The holster was cut down at one time to allow easier removal of the firearm. I am not sure if the returning Vet did this or if it was done by the original wartime owner. I bought this holster together with a 1918 Erfurt Luger (NFS) back around 1987 and have had both ever since. Luger is NOT for sale. Excellent period piece showing wartime use.
